title: Classic (Sells Mendel style) Bar Clamp, in two part harmony.

description.text:
When rebuilding my lasercut wooden printer, I decided that one of the things that could use improvement over the Prusa design was the bar clamps. Now that the Y carriage is non-adjustable, the position of the Y axis smooth rods relative to the frame is critical, and the Prusa style bar clamps don't do a good job of enforcing the spacing between the two rods. I looked at the original (Sells mendel) Bar clamps, and decided that with 3 parts, they were more complicated than I liked, so I designed these as a replacement. Revisions:
Â Â Â Â Reduced the slop on the nut traps from .5 to .25 - apparently my .35 nozzle doesn't shrink holes as much as the .5 nozzle did.

Vitamins: Â Â Â Â 4 M3 x 20 Socket head screws.
Â Â Â Â 4 M3 nylock nuts.
2 M8 nuts.
Â Â Â Â 2 M8 washers.
Â Â Â Â 2 M8 bars that need connecting. Print the parts, and clean the bridges out of the screw holes. Insert M3 nylock nuts into the nut traps. Assemble parts onto the threaded rod as follows: M8 nut, M8 washer, clamp bottom (the taller piece), M8 washer, M8 nut. Position the smooth rod, and position the clamp top on top of the smooth rod. Insert the M3 socket screws, and tighten them just enough to hold the pieces together, but not tight enough to stop them from moving. Fine tune your positioning of the smooth rod using the M8 nuts, and tighten the M8 nuts. Tighten the M3 socket screws. Note: In theory, you could leave off the M8 nuts and washers, but I find that they're indispensable for fine positioning.

description.text: This is a representation of the polarization of the radio signal coming from the pulsar PSR J0337+1715. This highly magnetized neutron star emits radio waves that sweep across the sky as it rotates hundreds of times per second. As we record these waves at Earth, we see a repetitive radio signal. Part of that signal is polarized, presumably by the magnetic field in the region where the emission is produced. This object illustrates the polarization. With an elliptically polarized radio wave, the tip of the electric field vector sweeps out a spiral. The elliptical shape of this spiral contains the polarization information: the direction and length of the long axis tell us about the linear polarization, and the length of the short axis tells us about the circular polarization, while the direction of the spiral tells us about the sign of the circular polarization.

Design

The raw data was acquired with the Green Bank Telescope in West Virginia. I took the polarization profile and constructed this spiral. I then used the Mayavi2 visualization tool to convert it to a tube, which I then saved to disk.

title: HOWTO: Fancy TTF and stick TTF fonts

description.text:
For many applications (engraving, laser cut etc.) are required “stick” TTF fonts but on web we can found only few of such fonts. Viceversa we can found many Open Source or Public Domain standard TTF fonts (see resources).

This tollchain and the Fontfilter java program are created to experiment with TTF fonts, to produce new fancy TTF font or font family, and as help to transform TTF fonts to stick TTF fonts.

The Fontfilter can process all glyphs presents in a font, so it is very fast and it is a great help on design new fonts.

Summary:

  • The Problem
  • Features
  • Toolchain
  • Notes and References

see the file HOWTO_TTFfonts_en.pdf or HOWTO_TTFfonts_it.pdf

The FontFilter is also here: https://github.com/msillano/FontFilter (w. sources)

INSTALLATION NOTES - WIN Preconditions:
  • java
  • Notepad++ (an ASCII editor)
  • StickFonts 1.1
  • FontForge
    • 1) download all fies in a dir writable (e.g. C:\myprogs\fontfilter)
    2) edit and modify the file dofilter.bat
    3) optional: Add a link on desktop to dofilter.bat using fontfilter.ico USE
    see toolchain in documents/HOWTO_TTFfonts_en.pdf
    (versione italiana: HOWTO_TTFfonts_it.pdf) 1) Convert the base TTF font to CHR using StickFont
    2) Edit configuration file fontfilter.ffc before to run dofilter.bat. Set:
    Input file

    Filter transformation and parameters
    Output file (SVG)
    note: the file fontfilter.fcc.model is the initial default. Don't change it. 3) Run filter using dofilter.bat
    4) Open the output SVG font in FontForge to see results
    5) Edit glyphs as required
    6) Save as TTF DEVELOPMENT

title: Onera HOR12 Airfoil Micro Drone Propeller (31.69g thrust @ 3V)

description.text:
I created this micro drone propeller by using the Onera HOR12 airfoil. It got tested on the Drone Propeller Thrust Testing Jig Results can be inspected below.

It was printed at a slow speed, by using a 0.2 extruder nozzle at 0.04mm layer height. The final part was cleaned using a Precision Knife

After this, I went on and sanded it with a small piece of 500 grit sandpaper.

Here are the thrust readings for some voltage values (you can also view these in the images):

  • 1.5V => 4.7 grams
  • 2V => 13.56 grams
  • 2.5V => 18.52 grams
  • 3V => 31.69 grams

The files you can download contain all the pictures taken during the test, with 6 text files that have all the airfoil coordinates used in the build, the printable STL files and finally the SLDPRT files. If you'd like to play with the propeller, you need to get a 8520 coreless motor.

You can use the SLDPRT files, should you wish to make your own changes to the propeller.

Notice: The airfoil plotted using the matplotlib library in python.

& just general research.

Designed for my Rockshox Recon Silver, 100 mm, G2 geometry fork.

You'll need:

  • shifter, an indexed one would probably be preferably. Right/left doesn't matter.
  • cable housing
  • shift cable
  • M5 bolt, just needs to be long enough
  • M5 nut: the inset is designed to fit one with 8.05 mm between parallel sides
  • an expansion spring: should be stiff enough to push your manual lockout switch to the open position (anti-clockwise). Mine is .70 mm thick, 35 mm long, 7.56 mm ID, 8.79 mm OD. There's a curved surface on the stop, etc. to permit a small range of springs.
  • Shimano cable anchor plate. These should be pretty common. Ask your LBS for a spare.

These 3D printed parts

  • fork steerer cable guide: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2301284
  • switch + cable anchor
  • cable stop

Mount your shifter, install your cable & housing length needed to reach the cable stop on the fork crown. Use the steerer cable guide to route the cable under the downtube & behind the fork crown.

Remove your existing lockout switch, but keep the coarsely threaded sheet metal screw that comes with it (mine is countersunk).

Slip the cable stop over. It will align in only 1 of 6 positions; I would choose the one closest to the back of the bicycle. Then slip the replacement switch + cable anchor piece on top. Secure the screw back on.

Run your cable through the spring, & add the Shimano anchor plate, then secure that with your M5 bolt & nut.

description.text:
From Prusa i4 to Prusa Z
Full documentation in the attached pdf file.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=amEFm7ViJs0

This work is being brought to you accompanied with a lot of thinking, coffee, lack of sleep and above all, love for open source and engineering. To appreciate my effort, all I ask you is to maintain the new names I will coin in here, otherwise, use as you like and share widely. Enjoy.
So let’s get started with the metamorphosis process. The aim is change your Prusa i4 to Prusa Z. Why? Besides the high speeds with exceptional print quality, Prusa Z comes with the following features:
1) Synchronised Z-axis screws.
2) Single motor driven Z-axis.
3) Dual Z-configuration hotend assemblies (Configuration adapted by Zahir to obtain maximum Temperature break as soon as you exit the heat block, great temperature profile - made up of 2 V6 Heatsinks, 2 throats and 1 cyclops Heat Block).
4) Two filaments in, one nozzle out (colour mixing possibilities).
5) Elimination of the extra weight on the X axis (you get super fast speeds)
6) X-axis motor moved off the hotend assembly

Well, they say pictures speak louder than words. I hope so. Note that I will not spend my time explaining screw sizes. Please figure that yourself. If you can't make a move at all, then leave a comment or write to me at: [email protected] If you also feel like paying so that I send you a complete package containing all the necessary modification pieces and firmware in a flash, write to me.

title: Creality CR-10 parametric spool holder bushings/adapter

description.text:
***** BEWARE: before you print this part, make sure you measure the outside diameter of the spool holder arm on your printer, several people have printed this part only to find out it doesn't fit their printer spool holder arm, it seems Creality used different diameter metal stock on their printers, I've heard comments that this is for the first generation of CR-10's.
If you decide you still want to print it and don't have a caliper to measure your spool holder arm diameter, then save yourself from disappointment and do the right thing: print just handful of layers, stop your print and make sure whatever you printed fits your spool holder arm.

I couldn't find a suitable bushing or holder adapter for the stock arm on the Creality CR-10 so i created this one on Fusion 360, the threads are virtually play free and i didn't alter sizes for tolerance, off the plate it threaded with no effort whatsoever, it actually cleaned all the fuzzies my current PETG leaves behind.

The adapter runs the length of the arm and holds the large spools i have firmly in place while rotating without effort, for much smaller spools like the one that comes with the printer i invert the female and it fits them perfectly.

I might add a hex or some sort of wings in the near future to help remove the nut since it fits very snug on the spools.

If you print and use this and run into spools with a larger than 60mm diameter and dont want or know how to alter it, let me know and i'll be happy to update it.

If you print it, please share your results, thank you.

title: Beaba baby cook lock and hinge spares

description.text:
My neighbours got a new baby and their Beaba babycook was ruined (seems to be designed not to endure more than one baby). The lock and one of the hinges was broken. They commented that they love the device because it is very practical. After seeing it I can understand it is practical, but it is definitely designed not to endure (so low quality for such a high price). Anyway, I decided to give them as present some spares so that they do not have to spend money in a new one.

As always, you have the FreeCAD sources (v0.17 PD NEXT) so that you can improve it or adapt it or whatever you wish.

The lock

I have never seen the full original part as they only handed over half of the original. The other half was gone (hopefully the first baby did not eat it). So I basically imagined how it could have been. It is not perfect. It is usable. It can certainly be improved.

The hinges

The original ones are plastic. The idea here is to print two of those tiny cylinders and put a M3x20 screw on each. Those are now real hinges that won't break.

Printer:

FABtotum with Zeus printing head

Resolution:

0.3 mm is enough

Infill:

solid

Notes:

I made it in PETG (I do not like ABS around food even if it is not in contact with it, PLA is too weak for locking mechanisms IMO).

I printed it full solid (100% infill).

Lock
I use slic3r as slicer. To print it without support I cut it in two just were the locking pin starts (Y = 23). See picture. Then glued the two together with superglue.

Hinges

Use a drill to make the hole real 3 mm.

You will probably need a brim for adhesion, as it has a tiny footprint.

You need to sand the lock very well because it slides on others, so you need to reduce friction.

If you wonder, in order to dissasemble the beaba bridge, you have to remove the back rubber caps on it (there are three). The one on the hinge allows to take the full bridge away and work comfortable.

FreeCAD. What else? ;)

I use the Ubuntu daily build (v.017) and the new Part Design NEXT workbench.

You have the sources attached.

This lamp looks like Twistlamp0 but I used a totally different way to define the geometry, so I have renamed it Domelight1. I printed this one with clear PLA to see how it looked with a color-changing LED inside. The LED is shown next to the lamp in the first photo. To find LED's that fit this light simply search for "LED puck light" and you will find lots of options. This light includes a small cutout at the bottom to accept a power cord if you pick a wall powered LED.

The photos show the light with the LED at different color phases. Here is a 42 second video showing how the light looks when the colors are changing: https://youtu.be/WTtG61yAouQ

Like TwistLamp0, this light is quite tall - it is 304 mm high, and this is a tricky size to print. Being that tall your printer might knock it over when it gets to the top most area since even a small amount of hotend drag on the part yields a large amount of sideways torque. Just to be safe I held on to the part for about the last 40 mm of printing. My next light will be shorter.

The camera is mounted upside down with the cooling/.25" mount installed. This way the camera can get rid of excess heat. You can configure the camera in mSetup to rotate the recording 180 degrees to compensate.

I have not managed to lose the camera while inside the full cover mount yet so it seems to be working.

The OpenSCAD sources are provided and there are some parameters which can be adjusted such as angle and height.

description.text:
This is a part designed to reduce the unwanted heatblock cooling by the hotend-fan of the tronxy x1. It is highly recommended to put some aluminium foil on the inside to further reduce heatloss as well as protecting the print from getting soft.

Tests showed reduction of heatup times from 30 sec to 2 minutes (190° to 230°).
The maximum reachable temperature with this part was 275° where the firmware wouldn't let me increase the head any further (probably to safe the assembly from overheating alltogether).
Whithout the part, the maximum heat topped out at about 230-245°

Printer:

Tronxy X1

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

Print in a orientation so that the layer aren't perpendicular to the overhanging surface.

Printed in PLA, there is the concern of the guard melting because of the heat. I did notice a slight sagging of the free hanging surface after heating the hotend up to 275° without the aluminium foil installed, But it didn't melt at all.
My guess is that with the foil installed, the distance from the heatblock and the constant cooling from the hotend fan is enought to keep the part save over long term.

description.text:
I had 3 goals when making this keyboard.

  1. I wanted a split keyboard, but I didn't want to have to relearn how to type.
    The thumb clusters on the ergodox or the layout of the keyboardio would have a learning curve that would require some muscle memory and it would be frustrating if I had to work on a laptop or someone else's keyboard.

  2. I wanted a keyboard that could be split and used individually. An Fn key on the thumb cluster could mirror the other half, so anyone with use of one hand could type relatively normally.

  3. I wanted to be able to find keycaps semi easily.
    The full keyboard has 70 keys, and can be filled with 1u keys from a 104 key set caps.
    The numpad/arrow/function keys of a full keycap set can be used on the thumb keys and modifiers of this keyboard.

I liked the overall design of the ergodox, but I didn't like the thumb cluster,
and I liked the keyboardio, but I didn't like the layout of the outer and inner most columns.
A normal keyboard is not symmetrical, so the layout on the keyboardio couldn't be standard.

For my specific layout I designed the layout on the outer most columns to be as close to a normal keyboard as I could

The left most column being esc, tab, Fn(to mimic the poker2 I was familiar with) shift and ctrl

The right most column being, backspace, ], enter, Fn(the firmware I used needed 2 Fn buttons, one for each half) and ctrl
I put the shift key to the left of the Fn key.

At this point, if all the thumb cluster was, was 8 spacebars, anyone could type on it normally with nearly 0 experience and nearly 0 learning curve.

The firmware I used was Soarer's Controller, A link can be found on this page.
https://deskthority.net/workshop-f7/soarer-s-keyboard-controller-firmware-t6767.html

I uploaded the 2 firmware files I used for my layout. splitkey-LEFT.sc and splitkey-RIGHT.sc

I recommend some rubber feet, the plastic alone will slide around on a desk.

Notes:

Depending on the material used for printing, you may need to scale up the files slightly.
Some of my Gateron switches would fit in the slots, but would be so tight wouldn't reset.
Also I printed with clear abs, and it shows some signs of cracks around some of the switches.

This cover is to prevent obstructions from entering the barrel, and if made correctly, is even waterproof.

Simply print it to scale, and it should be just a little bit too snug to slide over the end of the muzzle brake. Heat it with a lighter down the sides, and slide it on. When it cools it will shrink around the muzzle. Then just leave it on until you use it. description.text:
Finally, somewhere to put those blindingly bright LEDs. I also disliked the original one as its a touch screen, so why have the panel dangling around?

This one is solidly fixed right to the edge of the top panel. It sits flush to the edge so if you want to build an enclosure the screen can be easily accessible from the outside.

The LEDs are diffused and to a degree lights up the honeycomb infill which looks pretty cool. So I'd recommend printing in something translucent or white. There are two clips on the inside that hold the LEDs,

I recommend printing this in ABS.

You will need:
2 x M5 x 10mm screws (Original 2 screws to hold LCD panel, I THINK it is M5)
6 x M3 nuts
6 x M3 x 16mm or longer Countersunk

The way I put it together was first attaching the back panel to the frame mount. Passing through the cables and attaching it to the LCD screen. Then closing it up pulling away the cables from the top of the printer. Then screw in the 4 screws around the LCD panel (on the front mount).
